{"author":{"id":"68363a891cc29367ca932a82cfa1531e93a8f5d8a3d8b5f097a28113788cc5a6"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1767770118,"nonce":"rmvV7J5h1J5B5waDLmJTZ8Kv/GQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s7dllrG","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/7516#issuecomment-3717618374"},"message":"Hey, I’m the developer of `MiST`, and I would be very interested in helping to add it to Galaxy. We already have a working wrapper for `mist call` in our own Galaxy instance.\n\nHowever, there are some technical challenges in making this wrapper generally usable. In our local setup, database management (e.g.  downloading and updating MLST and cgMLST schemes) is handled by Galaxy admins, who make the schemes available to the `mist call` wrapper via a `.loc` file. For a ToolShed-based installation, I assume this would require a Galaxy data manager. However, we don’t yet have experience developing or maintaining data managers.\n\nI’d really appreciate feedback or guidance from an experienced ToolShed developer on the best approach here.\n\nAt a high level, the intended workflow is:\n```bash\nmist download --url {SCHEME_URL}\nmist index {DOWNLOAD_DIR}\nmist call {INDEX_DIR}\n```","files":null}]}